4 SYNOPSIS:
5 Under existing law, an individual may be
6 arrested without a warrant if the individual has been
7 charged in another state with a crime punishable by
8 death or life imprisonment.
9 This bill would provide that an individual may
10 be arrested without a warrant if the individual has
11 been charged in another state with a felony.
12 This bill would also authorize out-of-state law
13 enforcement officers to arrest individuals suspected of
14 committing a felony in the officer's home state at the
15 conclusion of a fresh pursuit.
16
17
18 A BILL
19 TO BE ENTITLED
20 AN ACT
21
22 Relating to criminal procedure; to amend Section
23 15-9-41, Code of Alabama 1975; to further provide for the
24 conditions under which an individual may be arrested without a
25 warrant; and to add Section 15-9-50 to the Code of Alabama
26 1975, to authorize arrests by out-of-state law enforcement
27 officers in certain circumstances.
28 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
Page 1

BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
SB114 INTRODUCED
29 Section 1. Section 15-9-41, Code of Alabama 1975, is
30 amended to read as follows:
31 "§15-9-41
32 (a) The arrest of a person may be lawfully made also by
33 an officer or a private citizen An officer or private citizen,
34 without a warrant, may lawfully arrest an individual upon
35 reasonable information that the accused individual stands
36 charged in the courts of another state with any of the
37 following:
38 (1) a A crime punishable by death or life .
39 (2) A crime punishable by imprisonment in the courts of
40 another statefor a term exceeding one year.
41 (3) Any crime otherwise punishable as a felony.
42 (b) When so arrestedFollowing an arrest pursuant to
43 subsection (a), the accused arrestee must be taken receive a
44 hearing before a district or circuit court judge with all
45 practicable speed and. A complaint must be made against him or
46 her under oath setting forth the ground for the arrest as in
47 Section 15-9-40,. and thereafter Thereafter, his or her answer
48 shall be heard as if he or she had been arrested on a
49 warrant."
50 Section 2. Section 15-9-50 is added to the Code of
51 Alabama 1975, to read as follows:
52 §15-9-50
53 (a) For the purposes of this section, the following
54 terms have the following meanings:
55 (1) ARRESTING OFFICER. An officer, employee, or agent
56 of any state or of any political subdivision of a state who is
Page 2

of any state or of any political subdivision of a state who is
SB114 INTRODUCED
57 required by law to: (i) maintain public order; (ii) make
58 arrests for offenses, whether that duty extends to all
59 offenses or is limited to specific offenses; and (iii)
60 investigate the commission or suspected commission of
61 offenses.
62 (2) FELONY. Any of the following crimes committed in
63 any state:
64 a. A crime punishable by death.
65 b. A crime punishable by imprisonment for a term
66 exceeding one year.
67 c. Any crime otherwise punishable as a felony.
68 (3) FRESH PURSUIT. a. The term includes, but is not
69 limited to, all of the following:
70 1. The term as defined by the common law.
71 2. The pursuit of an individual who has committed a
72 felony or who is reasonably suspected of having committed a
73 felony.
74 3. The pursuit of an individual suspected of having
75 committed a supposed felony, though no felony has actually
76 been committed, if there is reasonable ground for believing
77 that a felony has been committed.
78 b. The term does not necessarily imply instant pursuit,
79 but pursuit without unreasonable delay.
80 (4) POWER TO ARREST. The legal authority to arrest and
81 hold an individual in custody that is equivalent in scope to
82 an Alabama law enforcement officer's authority to arrest and
83 hold in custody an individual believed to have committed a
84 felony in this state.
Page 3

felony in this state.
SB114 INTRODUCED
85 (b) Any arresting officer of another state, while
86 engaged in fresh pursuit of an individual believed to have
87 committed a felony in that state, shall have the power to
88 arrest that individual in this state.
89 (c) Subsection (b) shall not be construed to make any
90 arrest in this state unlawful that would otherwise be lawful.
91 (d)(1) If an arrest is made in this state pursuant to
92 subsection (b), the arresting officer, without unnecessary
93 delay, shall take the individual before a district or circuit
94 judge for the county in which the arrest was made. The judge
95 shall conduct a hearing to determine the lawfulness of the
96 arrest.
97 (2)a. If the judge determines that the arrest was
98 lawful, he or she shall commit the individual to custody for a
99 reasonable time to await the issuance of an extradition
100 warrant or admit the individual to bail for the same purpose.
101 b. If the judge determines that the arrest was not
102 lawful, he or she shall discharge the individual.
103 Section 3. This act shall become effective immediately.
